'''Shigeoka Kawahito''' (滋岳川人) was a {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代}} aristocrat and {{ill|Onmyōji|ja|陰陽師}}. His family name transitioned from {{ill|Togi no Ason|ja|刀岐直}} to {{ill|Shigeoka no Ason|ja|滋岳朝臣}}. His court rank reached {{ill|Senior Fifth Rank, Upper Grade|ja|従五位上|1=Junior Fifth Rank|lt=Junior Fifth Rank, Upper Grade}}, and he served as the {{ill|Head of the Bureau of Onmyō|ja|陰陽頭}}.

== Lineage ==
The origins of the Togi clan (刀岐氏) are unclear, but they are thought to be descended from the {{ill|Mikata District|ja|美方郡}} Togi area in {{ill|Tajima Province|ja|但馬国}} (modern {{ill|Shin'onsen Town|ja|新温泉町}}, {{ill|Hyōgo Prefecture|ja|兵庫県}}){{sfn|Ōta|1963|loc=3908}}. As a clan with the "Na" surname (直), they may have also been part of the {{ill|Mikata Province Governors|ja|二方国造}} lineage.

== Career ==
In {{ill|Ninju 4|ja|仁寿4th year }} ({{ill|854|ja|854th year }}), Kawahito and his relatives, including Togi no Masaru (then serving as {{ill|Kazusa Province|ja|上総国}} Provincial Secretary), were granted the surname {{ill|Shigeoka no Ason|ja|滋岳朝臣}}. At the time, he held the rank {{ill|Senior Sixth Rank, Upper Grade|ja|正六位上|1=Senior Sixth Rank|lt=Senior Sixth Rank, Upper Grade}} and the positions {{ill|Junior Assistant of the Bureau of Onmyō|ja|陰陽権允}} and {{ill|Onmyō Hakase|ja|陰陽博士|1=Onmyō Hakase}}. Kawahito continued to serve as an Onmyō Doctor for more than 20 years, spanning the reigns of {{ill|Emperor Montoku|ja|文徳天皇}} and {{ill|Emperor Seiwa|ja|Emperor Seiwa}}, eventually ascending to {{ill|Head of the Bureau of Onmyō|ja|陰陽頭}}. As an Onmyōji, his activities are well documented:
- In {{ill|Tian'an 2|ja|天安2nd year }} ({{ill|858|ja|858th year }}), Kawahito, along with {{ill|Abe no Asomi|ja|安倍安仁}} and others, selected a burial site for {{ill|Emperor Montoku|ja|文徳天皇}} in the {{ill|Katsuno District|ja|葛野郡}}, {{ill|Yamashiro Province|ja|Yamashiro Province }}.<ref>『{{ill|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|ja|日本三代実録}}』天安2nd year 9月2日条</ref>
- In {{ill|Jōgan 1|ja|貞観元年}} ({{ill|859|ja|859th year }}), he and {{ill|Fujihara no Yamakage|ja|藤原山蔭}} performed a ritual in {{ill|Yoshino District|ja|吉野郡}}, {{ill|Yamato Province|ja|Yamato Province }} to prevent pestilence.<ref>『{{ill|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|ja|日本三代実録}}』貞観元年8月3日条</ref>
- In {{ill|Jōgan 5|ja|貞観5th year }} ({{ill|863|ja|863rd year }}), he conducted further rituals to address similar concerns.<ref>『日本三代実録』貞観5th year 2月1日条</ref>
Kawahito's activities significantly influenced the rituals and practices during this period, particularly in the establishment of the {{ill|Takamayama Festival|ja|高山祭}}.

== Works and Legacy ==
Kawahito is credited with foundational works in Japanese {{ill|Onmyōdō|ja|陰陽道}}, including 『{{ill|Seiyō Dōsei-kyō|ja|世要動静経}}』 and 『{{ill|Kinshū Shinjutsu Tonkō-sho|ja|滋川新術遁甲書}}』.<ref>{{ill|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|ja|日本三代実録}}貞観16年5月27日条</ref> Although these are lost, they heavily influenced subsequent practitioners and texts.

== Timeline of Ranks ==
* {{ill|Ninju 4|ja|仁寿4th year }}: Promoted to {{ill|Senior Fifth Rank|ja|従五位下|1=Junior Fifth Rank|lt=Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade}}
* {{ill|Jōgan 3|ja|貞観3rd year }}: Appointed {{ill|Assistant Governor of Harima Province|ja|播磨権大掾}}


